############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "niceTables.pl", "parserAssignment.pl", "contextForm.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ @x = (0..3); $f = Formula("x^2"); @y = map{$f->eval(x => $_)} (@x); Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y => 'Real'); parser::Assignment->Allow; parser::Assignment->Function("f"); $eq = Formula("f(x) = $f");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Write an equation in the form [`f(x)=\ldots`] suggested by the pattern in the table.
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML('[`x`]'), rowbottom => '2', midrule => '1',], PGML('[`f(x)`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[1]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[1]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[2]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[2]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[3]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[3]]`]'), ], ], align => 'rl', valign => 'middle',);@]* <<
[_]{$eq}{20}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION Looking for a relationship in each row here, we see that each output value is the square of the corresponding [`x`]-value. That may not be obvious to you. It comes down to recognizing what square numbers are. So the equation is [`[$eq]\text{.}`]
What if we had tried the approach we used in the previous exercise, comparing change from row to row in each column?
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML('[`x`]'), rowbottom => '2', midrule => '1',], PGML('[`f(x)`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'), ], [PGML('(add [`1`] from previous) [`[$x[1]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[1]]`] (add [`1`] from previous)'), ], [PGML('(add [`1`] from previous) [`[$x[2]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[2]]`] (add [`3`] from previous)'), ], [PGML('(add [`1`] from previous) [`[$x[3]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[3]]`] (add [`5`] from previous)'), ], ], align => 'rl', valign => 'middle',);@]* <<
Here, the rate of change is _not_ constant from one row to the next. While the [`x`]-values are increasing by [`1`] from row to row, the output values increase more and more from row to row. Do you notice that there is a pattern there as well? Mathematicians are interested in finding patterns and describing them.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
